Friends: this Epstein Investigation is so much bigger than you can imagine.  It is not only about justice for survivors—it is also about the institutions and systems that protected rich and powerful men they knew were abusing women and children: the banks, the government agencies, and other powerful people.   

Just as we’re seeing right before our very eyes—it’s continuing in this Administration and Congress as we speak. This Friday, we will depose Alex Acosta, the prosecutor at the center of an agreement that shielded Epstein and his co-conspirators from prosecution, and who was then given a Trump political appointment. The truth is out there. And, we will not stop until we find it.

Violence is never the answer. But, neither is silence.

The very foundation of our democracy was forged in the crucible of debate and the idea that our voices are our most powerful tool.

History will remember those who stood up, spoke up, and worked to protect our democracy and bend the arc of history towards justice.

This #SuicidePreventionWeek, I want to remind everyone that mental health matters, and nobody has to face their challenges alone. It takes courage to ask for help, and every one of us plays a role in creating a community of support and understanding.

Help is available. Call or text 988 to reach the Suicide and Crisis line. For New Mexicans, you can also call 1-855-NMCRISIS.

If you or someone you know is struggling, please reach out—help is here, and your life matters.

As a government shutdown is looming, costs of everything are up, and the White House is deploying troops to our cities—the GOP is over here in the House engaging in more politics of the absurd.

Pushing fake funding bills, trying to repeal protections for public lands, rewriting the history of January 6th—and helping to cover up the Epstein files for a White House that is threatening Members of Congress if they sign on to a discharge petition.

The survivors deserve justice. The American people deserve the truth. To my colleagues across the aisle—do what is right. The petition is right there at the desk.

For far too long, survivors of sexual violence have been silenced by systems built to protect the powerful—including in this Chamber.

Today, we met and heard the stories of the victims of Jeffrey Epstein—some of whom shared their stories for the first time ever. What they revealed is not only the trauma of hundreds (maybe thousands) of young women, but a cover-up of epic proportions involving the wealthy, the well-connected, and even our own government—all the way to the top.

Let me be clear: we will not stop. We will follow every thread, every document, and every bank record until there is justice. To every survivor out there: We see you. We believe you. And we are fighting for you.

#throwback: Five years ago at the height of the pandemic, we organized a statewide food and hunger program to help feed New Mexicans. 

Five years later, this food and agriculture network continues and has helped pass some of the boldest anti-child hunger legislation in the country and launched a statewide initiative to end hunger.  

But the fight isn’t over. As the Administration and GOP are slashing food and ag programs, we must stay strong—because no matter how difficult things get, we will take care of New Mexico and our people.

Friends—it’s been another crazy week in politics and we’ll be talking in the coming days about how we’re working to protect vital programs, our democratic rights, and fighting against corruption. 

But, today we’re closing out our series on New Mexico and how we’re investing in the future of our state. This includes helping to pass the largest Bipartisan Infrastructure bill in generations, the CHIPS and Science Act, and the Inflation Reduction Act to invest in made-in-America jobs and a clean energy future. 

These bills are bringing home millions of dollars of investments to our communities. Coupled with the largest expansion of military and veterans benefits through the PACT Act in decades and millions for home-grown New Mexico entrepreneurs and businesses, for Sandia National Labs, our universities, IPCC, and other organizations—we are building an economy where New Mexicans can not only have opportunity—but thrive and with dignity and pride!

Big news for Carrizozo! The Federal Aviation Administration has awarded $333,000 to the community to upgrade its airport and install a precision path indicator system! 

Airports are hubs for trade, travel, and connectivity, and I’m grateful for these upgrades!

To everyone out there who has sent letters and words of encouragement to my office—THANK YOU!

It is the greatest honor of my life to represent our communities in Congress. I’m in this fight for our communities and a brighter future for this country, and I won’t stop until we get there. ❤️

Investing in our communities means tackling our biggest challenges with meaningful solutions—investing in public safety, behavioral health, housing, and community programs.

Over the last several years, we’ve brought home millions in funding for public safety and behavioral health programs, including a new clinic in the International District, a sobering center in Albuquerque, housing and addiction recovery on the West Side, and a proposal for a first-of-its-kind behavioral health and resource center in Sandoval County in Bernalillo.  We’re delivering millions for technology and tools to help local law enforcement and first responders address crime and get drugs off the streets and new fire and emergency response centers in the East Mountains, Sandia Pueblo, and Valencia County.  And, we’ve brought home millions for affordable housing for families, seniors, and young people, Albuquerque’s first youth homeless shelter, and our first transitional housing campus for veterans. 

This is the work we do every day in our office.  Not sound bites, but sustained and dedicated investment in our communities and families and in transformational projects to help those who are struggling most.

Today, we remember the March on Washington—not just as a moment in history, but as a call to action.

Hundreds of thousands came together to demand jobs, freedom, and dignity, and marched not just for themselves, but for future generations—for civil rights, for economic justice, for the right to vote, and for an America that truly lives up to its promises. 

Now, more than ever the work continues.

Let’s be real about what Donald Trump and his Admin are doing—they are targeting Black women in leadership and threatening the stability of our economy—and nowhere is this more apparent than the attempt to fire Lisa Cook from the Federal Reserve.

Let us be clear—the President does not have this authority. And, an independent Fed is vital to the economic stability of our country, including retirements, investments, and the stability of everyday life. We stand with Lisa Cook and this fight for our country!

In New Mexico—our lands and waters are woven into the fabric of our cultures and ways of life. As we continue our series on how New Mexico is leading the way—we are talking today about our fight to protect our public lands, the sacred waters of the Rio Grande and our rivers and streams, and to ensure our communities have a climate-resilient and sustainable future. 

That’s why I am proud to have helped pass the largest climate and clean energy bill in American history, we passed bipartisan legislation for grid modernization and water data in the #NMLeg, and we’re bringing home millions of dollars in funding to support climate resilience, forest management, the clean energy economy, water infrastructure, and support for our farmers and ranchers.   

This work is essential to the future of our state and our planet. We won’t back down!

Absolutely heartbroken at the news of the mass shooting at the Annunciation Catholic School in Minneapolis today, and the loss of two children and at least 17 others injured. Our prayers are with the families and community. 💔

Every single major medical association in America has denounced conversion “therapy” for what it is: a cruel, harmful, and unscientific practice that has no place in modern medicine. 

As a member of the @EqualityCaucus, I am proud to have joined 186 Members of Congress in calling to uphold state bans on these cruel practices for minors. 

Our LGBTQ+ community must be loved, seen, and accepted for who they are and nothing less. Period. ❤️🏳️‍🌈

Today, we continue our series on New Mexico’s leadership and celebrate the 19th Amendment—celebrating women in leadership and New Mexico as one of only three states in the U.S. with a female majority legislature.  

In countless ways, these leaders are transforming our state, fighting for democracy, and protecting our rights.

As we mark the anniversary of the 19th Amendment—and the long overdue recognition of women’s rights to vote—we also recognize the generations of women who fought tirelessly to be heard, seen, and counted, and the ongoing fight today to protect these rights.  

As we are seeing daily, the work of building a more just and inclusive democracy didn’t end with the historic movements that expanded American rights. It lives daily in our continued fight for voting rights, equality, and justice for all. 

We must keep bending that arc toward justice—especially as our communities face new assaults on their rights and freedoms.

In countless ways—New Mexico is leading the way! This week, we are launching a new series on all the ways New Mexico is leading the way in transformational investments and policies for our communities.
 
Today, we start with education and investments in our young people—which are vital to our future. New Mexico leads as the first state in the nation to pass universal early childhood education and free college for all.

I am deeply proud to have led federal efforts to make these generational investments in the House and to deliver millions back to NM-01 for early childhood education, Head Start projects, funding for public schools, mobile health units, youth programs, and our local colleges and universities. Go Lobos!
 
As a former educator myself (and public school kid), I know just how vital and transformational these investments are!

Albuquerque is more than just a place where we live. It is a part of who we are. And, we are fiercely proud of our city!

It was such an honor to join @MayorKeller, the ABQ City Council, and local leaders last night for the State of the City.

From investments in housing, behavioral health, and public safety to investing in education, our young people, and the economy—we are delivering for our communities. And, in these unprecedented times, we are standing strong to defend our democracy, our rights, and our future. 💪

Just three years ago, we passed the largest climate and clean energy bill in American history with the Inflation Reduction Act.

Through this bill—utilities have invested millions in modernizing our electric grid, lowering energy costs, and spurring a clean energy and manufacturing renaissance in America. And, New Mexico has been leading the way.

But, since day one, the Trump Admin has launched an all-out assault on clean energy jobs, freezing funding, repealing critical investments in the Big Ugly Bill, driving utility prices up, and costing the U.S. 64,000 clean energy jobs since the end of last year.

That is 64,000 people who lost access to good-paying jobs, benefits, and the ability to put food on the table. 

This is the reality of Trump’s policies, and they know it. Real people are losing jobs, prices are going up, and the U.S. is falling behind. This is why we are fighting back!

Millions have raised their voices, including thousands in the streets yesterday calling for an immediate ceasefire in Gaza. The unrelenting and escalating violence, mass starvation, and annexation being carried out by Netanyahu and his allies are not only a blatant violation of humanitarian rights, but a blatant violation of international law.

New Mexicans are strong and resilient. Even those hardest hit by these devastating floods are standing with remarkable strength and determination. 

I was on the ground today in Ruidoso, witnessing the damage firsthand. Despite losing everything, New Mexicans are still showing up for each other in this moment of heartbreak. 💔

🚨 Breaking—the federal government has just signed our Federal Disaster Declaration for Ruidoso. Thank you to everyone who helped get it done! 🚨

Today, I'm proud to stand with leaders at every level—federal, state, tribal, county, and local and with the families who have lost loved ones, their homes, and everything they hold dear.

This is what it means to be New Mexican: resilience, compassion, strength, and showing up for our people.

From neighbors helping neighbors to first responders and tribal leadership offering help, we’re rallying to protect and rebuild. This recovery will take years, but our communities will get through.

To everyone affected: we see you, we grieve with you, and we will keep fighting for you. Please stay safe, follow evacuation orders, and know we’re working tirelessly to bring resources and relief every step of the way.

We’re wrapping up at the Emergency Operations Center in Ruidoso with @GovMLG, Mayor Crawford, and our federal, state and local partners and first responders. 

All of our partners are on the ground and coordinating closely, and the community is pouring its heart out to help families devastated by the floods. Thank you to everyone for supporting this community!

My team and I are here on the ground in Ruidoso to help support emergency response efforts after the tragic and catastrophic flooding that happened yesterday.

My heart is with everyone who has been impacted, and I want to thank all of the first responders once again who have been working tirelessly to help those in need. Please contact our office if you need assistance at (505) 346-6781.

My heart is with the families who have lost loved ones, those still missing, and the entire Ruidoso community reeling from the devastating floods that have ripped through the community. We stand with the families and community in grieving the loss of three lives, including two children tragically lost in the floods, and with all those injured, displaced, and still awaiting news of loved ones.

I want to thank the first responders, local officials, and friends and neighbors who are stepping up in this moment of heartbreak. We are currently on the ground in the community and working closely to support emergency response and recovery efforts. 
 
Along with Governor Lujan Grisham and New Mexico’s Congressional Delegation, we are continuing to fight for the federal resources to respond to this disaster, including the emergency disaster declaration we transmitted to the White House today. 

I and my team are in Ruidoso and Mescalero today and coming days to support emergency response efforts and to meet with local officials and families who have been impacted. 
 
For emergency updates and resources, please visit https://t.co/ZNCVmJWI4s. 
 
For those in need of emergency assistance, please call 911, and those in need of non-emergency recovery assistance, please call 1-833-663-4736. You can also call my office at any time for assistance at (505) 346-6781.

Thank you to everyone across New Mexico and the country who has reached out about the catastrophic floods in Ruidoso today. This afternoon, record rainfall fell on burn scars from last year’s fires, creating flood conditions through our beloved town of Ruidoso. As emergency response and rescue are still underway, we are in close coordination with federal, state, local and tribal governments and first responders.

If you are in the area, please continue to follow emergency evacuation orders and call 911 if you need emergency assistance. Our office is here to assist and help in every possible way we can—please contact us if you need assistance at (505) 346-6781.
